 266	## Pub/Sub
 267	
 268	### Server Setup
 269	
 270	Set up a dedicated application for handling events.
 271	
 272	```ts
 273	import { App } from '@deepkit/app';
 274	import { FrameworkModule } from '@deepkit/framework';
 275	import { RestateModule } from 'deepkit-restate';
 276	import { RestatePubsubServerModule } from 'deepkit-restate/pubsub-server';
 277	
 278	await new App({
 279	 imports: [
 280	 new FrameworkModule({ port: 9090 }),
 281	 new RestateModule({ server: { port: 9080 } }),
 282	 new RestatePubSubServerModule({
 283	 sse: {
 284	 all: true,
 285	 autoDiscover: true,
 286	 nodes: ['localhost:9090'],
 287	 },
 288	 }),
 289	 ],
 290	}).run();
 291	```
 292	
 293	### Publishing Events
 294	
 295	Inside a service handler (durable):
 296	
 297	```ts
 298	constructor(private readonly publisher: RestateEventPublisher) {}
...
 326	```
 327	
 328	### SSE Delivery
 329	
 330	Server-Sent Events (SSE) allow real-time delivery of events to connected subscribers.
 331	
 332	#### Subscribing to Events Outside of Services
 333	
 334	Subscribe to events from contexts like HTTP or RPC controllers:
 335	
 336	```ts
 337	const subscriber = app.get<RestateEventSubscriber>();
 338	
 339	const unsubscribe = await subscriber.subscribe<UserCreatedEvent>(event => {
 340	 // handle event
 341	});
 342	
 343	await unsubscribe();
 344	```
 345	
 346	You can also use union types to subscribe to multiple events.
 347	
 348	#### Configuration (Global)
 349	
 350	You can configure global SSE delivery behavior in `RestatePubSubServerModule`:
 351	
 352	```ts
 353	new RestatePubSubServerModule({
 354	 sse: {
 355	 all: true,
 356	 autoDiscover: true,
 357	 nodes: ['events-1.internal:9090', 'events-2.internal:9090'],
 358	 },
 359	});
 360	```
 361	
 362	| Option | Type | Description |
 363	|--------------------| ---------- |-------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
 364	| `sse.all` | `boolean` | If `true`, all published events will be delivered via SSE by default. |
 365	| `sse.autoDiscover` | `boolean` | When enabled, resolves peer IPs via DNS to fan out SSE events to other nodes. |
 366	| `sse.nodes` | `string[]` | List of peer server URLs for fan-out. |
 367	
 368	> SSE fan-out is stateless and opportunistic. Each node will attempt to push matching events to other known nodes.
 369	
 370	#### Overriding per Publish
 371	
 372	You can override the global SSE setting by passing `{ sse: true }` in the publish options:
 373	
 374	```ts
 375	await publisher.publish([new UserCreatedEvent(user)], {
 376	 sse: true,
 377	});
 378	```
 379	
 380	Behavior summary:
 381	
 382	- If `sse.all` is **true**, SSE is used by default unless explicitly disabled.
 383	- If `sse.all` is **false**, SSE is off by default but you can still enable it by passing `sse: true`.
 384	
 385	> Only events published with SSE enabled will be streamed to subscribers.
 386	
 387	# Sagas
 388	
 389	Sagas provide a powerful way to orchestrate complex, long-running workflows that involve multiple services. They support **stepwise execution**, **compensation (rollback)**, **reply handling**, and **waiting for external events** (via awakeables).
 390	
 391	---
 392	
 393	## What is a Saga?
 394	
 395	A **Saga** is a workflow pattern that manages distributed transactions and side effects in a coordinated way, including compensations for failures. In Deepkit Restate, you define sagas by extending the `Saga<T>` class and using the `@restate.saga<Api>()` decorator.
 396	
 397	---
 398	
 399	## Defining a Saga Workflow
 400	
 401	Sagas are defined using a fluent builder pattern in the `definition` property:
 402	
 403	- `step()`: Defines a new step in the saga.
 404	- `invoke(handler)`: Calls a method in your saga class to perform an action or service call.
 405	- `compensate(handler)`: Defines a rollback method if the step fails or the saga is aborted.
 406	- `onReply<EventType>(handler)`: Registers an event handler for replies to invoked actions.
 407	- `build()`: Finalizes the saga definition.
 408	
 409	---
 410	
 411	## Awakeables
 412	
 413	Awakeables are special constructs to **wait for asynchronous external events**. They provide a promise you can `await` to pause saga execution until an event occurs.
 414	
 415	Create awakeables with the saga context inside your saga methods:
 416	
 417	```ts
 418	this.confirmTicketAwakeable = this.ctx.awakeable<TicketConfirmed>();
 419	```
 420	
 421	---
 422	
 423	## Using the Saga Context
 424	
 425	The `RestateSagaContext` (`this.ctx`) provides utilities like:
 426	
 427	- `awakeable<T>()`: Creates an awakeable to wait for events.
 428	- `set<T>(key, value)`: Persist state data during saga execution.
 429	- `get<T>(key)`: Retrieve persisted state.
 430	
 431	---
 432	
 433	## Calling Other Services
 434	
 435	All service calls inside invocation handlers automatically use the underlying `client.call`. This means:
...
 550	
 551	- The saga `start` call triggers the first step of your saga workflow.
 552	- The saga state reflects all persisted data and progress, useful for monitoring or troubleshooting.
 553	- You can invoke `start` only once per unique saga instance ID.
 554	- Subsequent state changes happen asynchronously as the saga progresses.
 555	
 556	### Summary
 557	
 558	- Sagas manage multi-step distributed workflows with clear compensation.
 559	- Steps can invoke service calls, wait for replies, or wait for external events.
 560	- Awakeables let you asynchronously wait inside sagas for external confirmations.
 561	- Saga state can be persisted and retrieved with the saga context.
 562	- Invocation handlers automatically handle calling services; no manual client calls needed.
 563	- Currently, only service calls are supported, no direct object calls with keys.
 564	- Compensation methods help rollback on failure or abort scenarios.
