 1	# Deepkit Restate
 2	
 3	**Deepkit Restate** is a seamless [Restate](https://restate.dev) integration for [Deepkit](https://deepkit.io). It enables effortless communication between distributed services using durable invocations, service interfaces, and event-driven architecture.
 4	
 5	> This documentation assumes familiarity with Deepkit **and** Restate's concepts and lifecycle.
 6	
 7	---
 8	
 9	## Installation
 10	
 11	```bash
 12	npm add deepkit-restate
 13	```
 14	
 15	---
 16	
 17	## Module Setup
 18	
 19	To use Deepkit Restate, import the `RestateModule` and provide configuration for the components you need:
 20	
 21	```ts
 22	import { FrameworkModule } from '@deepkit/framework';
 23	import { RestateModule } from 'deepkit-restate';
 24	import { App } from '@deepkit/app';
 25	
 26	const app = new App({
 27	 imports: [
 28	 new FrameworkModule(),
 29	 new RestateModule({
 30	 server: {
 31	 host: 'http://localhost',
 32	 port: 9080,
 33	 propagateIncomingHeaders: true, // Forward all incoming headers to service calls
 34	 },
 35	 ingress: {
 36	 url: 'http://localhost:8080',
 37	 },
 38	 pubsub: {
 39	 cluster: 'default',
 40	 defaultStream: 'all',
 41	 sse: {
 42	 url: 'http://localhost:3000',
 43	 },
 44	 },
 45	 admin: {
 46	 url: 'http://0.0.0.0:9070',
 47	 deployOnStartup: true,
 48	 },
 49	 }),
 50	 ],
 51	});
 52	```
 53	
 54	You can configure any combination of the following:
 55	
 56	- **server**: Starts a Restate server
 57	- **ingress**: Enables outbound service calls
 58	- **pubsub**: Enables pub/sub event system
 59	- **admin**: Registers deployments with the admin interface
 60	
 61	> If a section is not configured, that functionality will not be available.
 62	
 63	## Server Configuration
 64	
 65	The `server` configuration section supports the following options:
 66	
 67	| Option | Type | Default | Description |
 68	|--------|------|---------|-------------|
 69	| `host` | `string` | - | The host address for the Restate server |
 70	| `port` | `number` | `9080` | The port number for the Restate server |
 71	| `propagateIncomingHeaders` | `true \| string[]` | `undefined` | Controls header propagation to downstream service calls |
 72	
 73	### Header Propagation
 74	
 75	The `propagateIncomingHeaders` option controls whether incoming request headers are forwarded when making service-to-service calls:
 76	
 77	```ts
 78	// Forward all incoming headers
 79	server: {
 80	 propagateIncomingHeaders: true
 81	}
 82	
 83	// Forward only specific headers
 84	server: {
 85	 propagateIncomingHeaders: ['authorization', 'x-correlation-id', 'x-tenant-id']
 86	}
 87	
 88	// No header propagation (default)
 89	server: {
 90	 // propagateIncomingHeaders not specified
 91	}
 92	```
 93	
 94	This is particularly useful for:
 95	- **Authentication**: Forwarding authorization tokens through the service call chain
 96	- **Tracing**: Propagating correlation IDs for distributed tracing
 97	- **Multi-tenancy**: Passing tenant identifiers to downstream services
 98	- **Custom context**: Forwarding application-specific headers
 99	
 100	> **Note**: When `propagateIncomingHeaders` is enabled, the incoming headers are merged with any explicitly provided headers in the service call options. Explicitly provided headers take precedence over incoming headers.
 101	
 102	---
 103	
 104	## Serialization (Serde) and Error Handling
 105	
 106	All serialization and deserialization in Deepkit Restate is handled via **BSON** by default.
 107	
 108	This means you can **return** and **accept** any types in your service handlers or saga steps, including:
 109	
 110	- Primitives (`string`, `number`, `boolean`, etc.)
 111	- Plain objects (`{ name: string; age: number }`)
 112	- Class instances (with properties and methods)
 113	- Complex nested types and arrays
 114	- Custom types supported by BSON serialization
 115	
 116	The serialization system preserves type fidelity and structure when encoding and decoding data across the network.
 117	
 118	### Automatic Error Forwarding and Serialization
 119	
 120	- If an error is **thrown** inside a handler or saga step, it is automatically serialized and forwarded to the caller.
 121	- This allows errors to be **caught** remotely, preserving the error information.
 122	- **Custom errors with type information** are supported and **will not be retried** automatically by the system, enabling precise control over error handling and retries.
 123	
 124	> We are actively working on an adapter to support JSON serialization as an alternative to BSON.
 125	
 126	---
 127	
 128	## Calling Services
 129	
 130	### `RestateClient`
 131	
 132	The `RestateClient` handles communication between services and objects. It behaves differently depending on whether it is used within or outside an invocation context.
 133	
 134	You can create an ingress client manually:
 135	
 136	```ts
 137	import { RestateIngressClient } from 'deepkit-restate';
 138	
 139	const client = new RestateIngressClient({ url: 'http://localhost:9080' });
 140	```
 141	
 142	Or retrieve the configured instance via DI:
 143	
 144	```ts
 145	const client = app.get<RestateClient>();
 146	```
 147	
 148	### Using the Client
 149	
 150	To create a proxy to a **service**:
 151	
 152	```ts
 153	const user = client.service<UserServiceApi>();
 154	```
 155	
 156	To create a proxy to an **object**:
 157	
 158	```ts
 159	const user = client.object<UserObjectApi>();
 160	```
 161	
 162	### Invoking Methods
 163	
 164	Durable request (waits for a result):
 165	
 166	```ts
 167	await client.call(user.create());
 168	```
 169	
 170	Fire-and-forget (does not wait for result):
 171	
 172	```ts
 173	await client.send(user.create());
 174	```
 175	
 176	You can configure delivery options:
 177	
 178	```ts
 179	await client.send(user.create(), { delay: '10s' });
 180	```
 181	
 182	For object calls, specify the key:
 183	
 184	```ts
 185	await client.call('user-key', user.create());
 186	await client.send('user-key', user.create());
 187	```
 188	
 189	---
 190	
 191	## Defining Services and Objects
 192	
 193	### Services
 194	
 195	```ts
 196	interface UserServiceHandlers {
 197	 create(username: string): Promise<User>;
 198	}
 199	
 200	type UserServiceApi = RestateService<'user', UserServiceHandlers>;
 201	
 202	@restate.service<UserServiceApi>()
 203	class UserService implements UserServiceHandlers {
 204	 constructor(private readonly ctx: RestateServiceContext) {}
 205	
 206	 @restate.handler()
 207	 async create(username: string): Promise<User> {
 208	 return User.create(this.ctx, username);
 209	 }
 210	}
 211	```
 212	
 213	- Use `@restate.service()` to define a service.
 214	- Use `@restate.handler()` define handlers.
 215	- The context (`RestateServiceContext`) provides durable execution helpers.
 216	
 217	### Objects
 218	
 219	```ts
 220	interface UserObjectHandlers {}
 221	
 222	type UserObjectApi = RestateObject<'user', UserObjectHandlers>;
 223	
 224	@restate.object<UserObjectApi>()
 225	class UserObject implements UserObjectHandlers {}
 226	```
 227	
 228	Use `@restate.object()` to define virtual objects.
 229	
 230	> Shared handlers can be declared using `@restate.shared().handler()`.
 231	> **Note:** Shared handlers use the object context, which is not type-safe. Avoid using `ctx.set()` at runtime in shared handlers.
 232	
 233	---
 234	
 235	## Dependency Injection: Calling Other Services
 236	
 237	You can inject the client and proxy APIs into a service:
 238	
 239	```ts
 240	@restate.service<UserServiceApi>()
 241	class UserService {
 242	 constructor(
 243	 private readonly client: RestateClient,
 244	 private readonly payment: PaymentServiceApi,
 245	 ) {}
 246	
 247	 @restate.handler()
 248	 async create(user: User): Promise<void> {
 249	 await this.client.call(this.payment.create('Test', user));
 250	 }
 251	}
 252	```
 253	
 254	For objects, remember to provide a key:
 255	
 256	```ts
 257	await this.client.call('payment-id', this.payment.create('Test'));
 258	```
 259	
 260	---
 261	
 262	## Durable Helpers
 263	
 264	### `run` blocks
 265	
 266	The `ctx.run()` helper ensures a block is executed durably:
 267	
 268	```ts
 269	const user = await this.ctx.run<User>('create user', () => new User(username));
 270	```
 271	
 272	Without a type argument, the return value is ignored:
 273	
 274	```ts
 275	const none = await this.ctx.run('create user', () => new User(username));
 276	```
 277	
 278	### Awakeables
 279	
 280	Used to pause and resume execution:
 281	
 282	```ts
 283	const awakeable = this.ctx.awakeable<User>();
 284	```
 285	
 286	To resume:
 287	
 288	```ts
 289	this.ctx.resolveAwakeable<User>();
 290	```
 291	
 292	### Durable State
 293	
 294	Store and retrieve durable state using the context:
 295	
 296	```ts
 297	await this.ctx.set<User>('user', user);
 298	```
 299	
 300	```ts
 301	const user = await this.ctx.get<User>('user');
 302	```
 303	
 304	---
 305	
 306	## Pub/Sub
 307	
 308	### Server Setup
 309	
 310	Set up a dedicated application for handling events.
 311	
 312	```ts
 313	import { App } from '@deepkit/app';
 314	import { FrameworkModule } from '@deepkit/framework';
 315	import { RestateModule } from 'deepkit-restate';
 316	import { RestatePubsubServerModule } from 'deepkit-restate/pubsub-server';
 317	
 318	await new App({
 319	 imports: [
 320	 new FrameworkModule({ port: 9090 }),
 321	 new RestateModule({ server: { port: 9080 } }),
 322	 new RestatePubSubServerModule({
 323	 sse: {
 324	 all: true,
 325	 autoDiscover: true,
 326	 nodes: ['localhost:9090'],
 327	 },
 328	 }),
 329	 ],
 330	}).run();
 331	```
 332	
 333	### Publishing Events
 334	
 335	Inside a service handler (durable):
 336	
 337	```ts
 338	constructor(private readonly publisher: RestateEventPublisher) {}
 339	
 340	await this.publisher.publish([new UserCreatedEvent(user)]);
 341	```
 342	
 343	Outside of invocation (non-durable):
 344	
 345	```ts
 346	const publisher = app.get<RestateEventPublisher>();
 347	await publisher.publish([new UserCreatedEvent(user)]);
 348	```
 349	
 350	> Only classes are supported as events.
 351	
 352	> Events are versioned by hashing their structure.
 353	
 354	### Handling Events
 355	
 356	Only services can define event handlers:
 357	
 358	```ts
 359	@restate.service<UserServiceApi>()
 360	class UserService {
 361	 @(restate.event<UserCreatedEvent>().handler())
 362	 async onUserCreated(event: UserCreatedEvent): Promise<void> {
 363	 // handle event
 364	 }
 365	}
 366	```
 367	
 368	### SSE Delivery
 369	
 370	Server-Sent Events (SSE) allow real-time delivery of events to connected subscribers.
 371	
 372	#### Subscribing to Events Outside of Services
 373	
 374	Subscribe to events from contexts like HTTP or RPC controllers:
 375	
 376	```ts
 377	const subscriber = app.get<RestateEventSubscriber>();
 378	
 379	const unsubscribe = await subscriber.subscribe<UserCreatedEvent>(event => {
 380	 // handle event
 381	});
 382	
 383	await unsubscribe();
 384	```
 385	
 386	You can also use union types to subscribe to multiple events.
 387	
 388	#### Configuration (Global)
 389	
 390	You can configure global SSE delivery behavior in `RestatePubSubServerModule`:
 391	
 392	```ts
 393	new RestatePubSubServerModule({
 394	 sse: {
 395	 all: true,
 396	 autoDiscover: true,
 397	 nodes: ['events-1.internal:9090', 'events-2.internal:9090'],
 398	 },
 399	});
 400	```
 401	
 402	| Option | Type | Description |
 403	|--------------------| ---------- |-------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
 404	| `sse.all` | `boolean` | If `true`, all published events will be delivered via SSE by default. |
 405	| `sse.autoDiscover` | `boolean` | When enabled, resolves peer IPs via DNS to fan out SSE events to other nodes. |
 406	| `sse.nodes` | `string[]` | List of peer server URLs for fan-out. |
 407	
 408	> SSE fan-out is stateless and opportunistic. Each node will attempt to push matching events to other known nodes.
 409	
 410	#### Overriding per Publish
 411	
 412	You can override the global SSE setting by passing `{ sse: true }` in the publish options:
 413	
 414	```ts
 415	await publisher.publish([new UserCreatedEvent(user)], {
 416	 sse: true,
 417	});
 418	```
 419	
 420	Behavior summary:
 421	
 422	- If `sse.all` is **true**, SSE is used by default unless explicitly disabled.
 423	- If `sse.all` is **false**, SSE is off by default but you can still enable it by passing `sse: true`.
 424	
 425	> Only events published with SSE enabled will be streamed to subscribers.
 426	
 427	# Sagas
 428	
 429	Sagas provide a powerful way to orchestrate complex, long-running workflows that involve multiple services. They support **stepwise execution**, **compensation (rollback)**, **reply handling**, and **waiting for external events** (via awakeables).
 430	
 431	---
 432	
 433	## What is a Saga?
 434	
 435	A **Saga** is a workflow pattern that manages distributed transactions and side effects in a coordinated way, including compensations for failures. In Deepkit Restate, you define sagas by extending the `Saga<T>` class and using the `@restate.saga<Api>()` decorator.
 436	
 437	---
 438	
 439	## Defining a Saga Workflow
 440	
 441	Sagas are defined using a fluent builder pattern in the `definition` property:
 442	
 443	- `step()`: Defines a new step in the saga.
 444	- `invoke(handler)`: Calls a method in your saga class to perform an action or service call.
 445	- `compensate(handler)`: Defines a rollback method if the step fails or the saga is aborted.
 446	- `onReply<EventType>(handler)`: Registers an event handler for replies to invoked actions.
 447	- `build()`: Finalizes the saga definition.
 448	
 449	---
 450	
 451	## Awakeables
 452	
 453	Awakeables are special constructs to **wait for asynchronous external events**. They provide a promise you can `await` to pause saga execution until an event occurs.
 454	
 455	Create awakeables with the saga context inside your saga methods:
 456	
 457	```ts
 458	this.confirmTicketAwakeable = this.ctx.awakeable<TicketConfirmed>();
 459	```
 460	
 461	---
 462	
 463	## Using the Saga Context
 464	
 465	The `RestateSagaContext` (`this.ctx`) provides utilities like:
 466	
 467	- `awakeable<T>()`: Creates an awakeable to wait for events.
 468	- `set<T>(key, value)`: Persist state data during saga execution.
 469	- `get<T>(key)`: Retrieve persisted state.
 470	
 471	---
 472	
 473	## Calling Other Services
 474	
 475	All service calls inside invocation handlers automatically use the underlying `client.call`. This means:
 476	
 477	- You **do not need to manually call `client.call`** within your saga handlers.
 478	- Only **service calls** are supported currently (no direct calls to objects).
 479	- The framework handles communication and reply handling.
 480	
 481	---
 482	
 483	## Example: Simplified CreateOrderSaga
 484	
 485	```ts
 486	import {
 487	 restate,
 488	 Saga,
 489	 RestateSagaContext,
 490	 RestateAwakeable,
 491	} from 'deepkit-restate';
 492	
 493	@restate.saga<CreateOrderSagaApi>()
 494	export class CreateOrderSaga extends Saga<CreateOrderSagaData> {
 495	 confirmTicketAwakeable?: RestateAwakeable<TicketConfirmed>;
 496	
 497	 readonly definition = this.step()
 498	 .invoke(this.create)
 499	 .compensate(this.reject)
 500	 .step()
 501	 .invoke(this.createTicket)
 502	 .onReply<TicketCreated>(this.handleTicketCreated)
 503	 .step()
 504	 .invoke(this.waitForTicketConfirmation)
 505	 .build();
 506	
 507	 constructor(
 508	 private readonly order: OrderServiceApi,
 509	 private readonly kitchen: KitchenServiceApi,
 510	 private readonly ctx: RestateSagaContext,
 511	 ) {
 512	 super();
 513	 }
 514	
 515	 create(data: CreateOrderSagaData) {
 516	 return this.order.create(data.orderId, data.orderDetails);
 517	 }
 518	
 519	 reject(data: CreateOrderSagaData) {
 520	 return this.order.reject(data.orderId);
 521	 }
 522	
 523	 createTicket(data: CreateOrderSagaData) {
 524	 this.confirmTicketAwakeable = this.ctx.awakeable<TicketConfirmed>();
 525	 return this.kitchen.createTicket(
 526	 data.orderDetails.restaurantId,
 527	 data.orderId,
 528	 data.orderDetails.lineItems,
 529	 this.confirmTicketAwakeable.id,
 530	 );
 531	 }
 532	
 533	 handleTicketCreated(data: CreateOrderSagaData, event: TicketCreated) {
 534	 data.ticketId = event.ticketId;
 535	 }
 536	
 537	 async waitForTicketConfirmation(data: CreateOrderSagaData) {
 538	 await this.confirmTicketAwakeable!.promise;
 539	 }
 540	}
 541	```
 542	
 543	## Starting a Saga and Retrieving Its State
 544	
 545	After defining your saga, you typically want to **start** an instance of it and later **query its state** to track progress or outcome.
 546	
 547	### Creating a Saga Client
 548	
 549	Use the client to create a saga proxy:
 550	
 551	```ts
 552	const createOrderSaga = client.saga<CreateOrderSagaApi>();
 553	```
 554	
 555	This creates a handle to interact with the saga.
 556	
 557	---
 558	
 559	### Starting a Saga Instance
 560	
 561	To start a saga, call `start` with the sagas unique ID and initial input data:
 562	
 563	```ts
 564	const startStatus = await createOrderSaga.start(orderId, {
 565	 id: orderId,
 566	 orderTotal: 10.5,
 567	 customerId,
 568	});
 569	```
 570	
 571	- `orderId` uniquely identifies the saga instance.
 572	- The second argument is the initial data payload to pass to the saga.
 573	- `start` returns the initial status of saga execution.
 574	
 575	---
 576	
 577	### Querying the Saga State
 578	
 579	At any time, you can query the current state of the saga instance by its ID using `state`:
 580	
 581	```ts
 582	const state = await createOrderSaga.state(orderId);
 583	```
 584	
 585	This returns the persisted saga data reflecting its current progress, e.g., which step it is on, and any state variables updated along the way.
 586	
 587	---
 588	
 589	### Notes
 590	
 591	- The saga `start` call triggers the first step of your saga workflow.
 592	- The saga state reflects all persisted data and progress, useful for monitoring or troubleshooting.
 593	- You can invoke `start` only once per unique saga instance ID.
 594	- Subsequent state changes happen asynchronously as the saga progresses.
 595	
 596	### Summary
 597	
 598	- Sagas manage multi-step distributed workflows with clear compensation.
 599	- Steps can invoke service calls, wait for replies, or wait for external events.
 600	- Awakeables let you asynchronously wait inside sagas for external confirmations.
 601	- Saga state can be persisted and retrieved with the saga context.
 602	- Invocation handlers automatically handle calling services; no manual client calls needed.
 603	- Currently, only service calls are supported, no direct object calls with keys.
 604	- Compensation methods help rollback on failure or abort scenarios.
 605	
